A homotopical category is a category equipped with a collection of morphisms W, called the weak equivalences, which contains the isomorphisms and satisfies the two-of-six property (hence is closed under composition and so forms a wide subcategory). A homotopical functor is a functor which preserves weak equivalences; the category of homotopical categories is so defined.
An additive category is a preadditive category with finite direct sums. (In particular, it has nullary direct sums, hence a zero object.)

A chain complex in an additive category is a \mathbb {Z}-graded sequence of objects \{x_i\} equipped with maps x_i\xrightarrow {\text {d}_i} x_{i-1}, called differentials, so that x_{i+1}\xrightarrow {\text {d}_{i+1}}x_i\xrightarrow {\text {d}_i}x_{i-1} = 0. We often omit the index on the differentials, so that the equation asks simply \text {d}^2 = 0.
Dually, a cochain complex has differentials written in the opposite direction, i.e. so x_i\xrightarrow {\text {d}_i} x_{i+1}.
If a chain complex is graded in some connected subset of \mathbb {Z}, for instance \mathbb {N}, then it extends to a chain complex in a unique way by filling in with zero objects.

An explicit construction is as follows: given a set A, we let \mathcal {F} A be the set of finitely supported formal \mathbb {Z}-linear combinations \sum _{a\in A} c_a a in A, with pointwise addition.

Let G be a group and N\unlhd G. Then there is a lattice isomorphism between the lattice of subgroups of G containing N and the lattice of subgroups of the quotient G/N, which sends N\leq A\leq G to A/N. Moreover, this assignment preserves and reflects normality.

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: Let C have (L, R)-factorizations. Then L and R are the respective orthogonal classes if and only if (L, R) forms a (strong) factorization system.

The orbit of an element a\in A of a G-set A is the image of a under G, i.e. Ga := \{g\cdot a: g\in G\}; by invertibility in G, the orbits form an equivalence relation.
By the monadicity theorem, the free-forgetful adjunction between Set and Grp is monadic.
Set is cartesian closed.
A subgroup is a subobject in Grp, written H\leq G; equivalently, it is a subset closed under the group operations.
The cyclic group C_n is the group of integers under the relation a\sim n whenever a - b divides n.
The dihedral group D_n is the group of symmetries of a regular n-gon.
The singular simplicial complex of a space X is a Kan complex.

fr:link.title: A leisurely introduction to simplicial sets

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: The simplex category is generated by the coface maps d^i: n\hookrightarrow n+1 which miss i, and the codegeneracy maps s^i: n+1\twoheadrightarrow n which repeat i. (By convention, we drop the dependence of d^i and s^i on n.) In particular, it is presented by maps of these types satisfying five simplicial identities.
The collection J(x) of covering sieves of an object x in a Grothendieck topology is like the collection of covers of an open set U in the poset of opens in a space X. In particular,:

fr:ul.fr:li: the identity axiom corresponds to the fact that \{U\} covers U;
the stability axiom corresponds to the fact that, if \{U_i\} covers U and V\subseteq U, then \{U_i\cap V\} covers V;
the transitivity axiom corresponds to the fact, if \{U_i\}_i covers U and \{U_{ij}\}_j covers U_i, then \{U_{ij}\}_{ij} covers U.

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: Let C^\text {op}\xrightarrow {F} Set be a presheaf for C locally small. Then F is the colimit of the diagram \text {el}(F)\xrightarrow {\Pi } C\xhookrightarrow {y} \hat {C}, where y is the Yoneda embedding.
A category is finite if it has only finitely many morphisms.

Let I\times J\xrightarrow {F} C be a bifunctorial diagram such that the limits \operatorname *{lim}_I \operatorname *{lim}_J F and \operatorname *{lim}_J \operatorname *{lim}_I F exist. Then \operatorname *{lim}_{I\times J} F exists, and the three limits are isomorphic.

Since representable isomorphism implies isomorphism, it suffices to prove that C(X, \operatorname *{lim}_I \operatorname *{lim}_J F) \cong C(X, \operatorname *{lim}_{I\times J} F) \cong C(X, \operatorname *{lim}_J \operatorname *{lim}_I F) naturally in X. Since hom functors preserve limits, the desired result becomes \operatorname *{lim}_I \operatorname *{lim}_J C(X, F) \cong \operatorname *{lim}_{I\times J} C(X, F) \cong \operatorname *{lim}_J \operatorname *{lim}_I C(X, F); i.e., the general case reduces to that of Set. By the isomorphism I\times J\cong J\times I, it suffices to prove the first isomorphism.

The proof is essentially by currying. Let I\times J\xrightarrow {G} Set be a diagram. By the construction of limits in Set, the limit \operatorname *{lim}_J G(i, -) is the set of cones over G(i, -) with summit *, hence equivalently the set of J-tuples (x_j\in G(i, j)) satisfying G(i, f)(x_j) = x_{j'} for each j\xrightarrow {f}j'\in J. Taking the limit over I, we now conclude that \operatorname *{lim}_I \operatorname *{lim}_J G consists of the tuples (x_{ij}\in G(i, j)) which commute with G-images of maps in I and J. This is exactly the data of \operatorname *{lim}_{I\times J} G.
Set is cocomplete.

By the cocompleteness criterion, it suffices to give coproducts and coequalizers. Coproducts are given by the disjoint union. The coequalizer of functions A\overset {f,g}{\rightrightarrows } B is B / \sim , where \sim is the equivalence relation generated by f(a) \sim g(a) for all a \in A, and / denotes the quotient of sets.
Cat is cocomplete.
The disjoint union is the coproduct in Set. Explicitly, the disjoint union of sets A and B is A \sqcup B = \{(a, 0) \mid a \in A\} \cup \{(b, 1) \mid b \in B\}, where \cup denotes the union.

fr:title.text: Limits and colimits in functor categories are computed pointwise

fr:frontmatter.fr:title: Limits and colimits in functor categories are computed pointwise

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: Let A be a small category. Then where \operatorname *{obj} C is the discrete category of objects, the forgetful functor C^A\to C^{\operatorname *{obj} A} strictly creates all limits and colimits in C. For each a\in A, the evaluation at a functor C^A\to C preserves all limits and colimits which exist in C.

Let C\xrightarrow {F} Set be a functor. The category of elements \text {el}(F) is the comma category *\downarrow F, where *\xrightarrow {*} Set is the inclusion of the point into the singleton set. Explicitly, the category of elements has:

fr:ul.fr:li: as objects, pairs (c, x) where c\in C and x\in Fc;
as morphisms (c, x)\to (d, y), morphisms c\xrightarrow {f} d in C such that Ff(x) = y;
composition and identities inherited from C.

fr:mainmatter.fr:p: The category of elements is further endowed with a forgetful functor \text {el}(F)\xrightarrow {\Pi } C sending (c, x) to c.
For any ordinal \alpha , there is a preorder whose objects are the smaller ordinals with the usual order.
When we say "the" X, we sometimes mean the unique X up to coherent or canonical isomorphism.
The category of topological spaces Top is the category whose objects are topological spaces and whose morphisms are continuous functions.
The direct image functor \mathcal {P}: Set\to Set takes a set to its powerset and a map X\xrightarrow {f}Y to its action f_* by direct images, i.e. f_*(A) = \{y\in Y :\exists x\in A, f(x) = y\}.
A homeomorphism is an isomorphism in Top. Explicitly, it is a continuous bijection with continuous inverse.
The inverse image functor \mathcal {P}: Set^\text {op}\to Set takes a set to its powerset and a map X\xrightarrow {f}Y to its action f^{-1} by inverse images, i.e. f_*(A) = \{x\in X: f(x)\in A\}.
